She organizes a group called Living Black Cully whose goals are to connect people of the African Diaspora and descendants of all African peoples within the larger Cully community. She wants to see a vibrant and ephemeral community.  
She is here to build authentic relationships, to organize around the TIF project, and to create programming to address her community’s specific needs and desires. Alagia leads with a grassroots approach to community engagement, outreach, event planning & coordination, youth programming, land preservation, cultivation, and restoration–all while centering collective community healing. Alagia knows that once Black people (people of African descent) have equity and autonomy, everyone, globally, can flourish.

fields.BIO:
I'm a publisher and writer for 30 years and author of 6 books on issues pertaining to the Afrikan Diaspora in the field of history, spirituality, health, culture, economics, interlaced to what Ishangi terms as ‘Self-determined Sustainability'. My latest book, 'A Pot to Piss In: Intergenerational Wealth Planning For Black People’ is self explanitory.

I focus on how cultural resuscitation can only happen with the tenets of financial literacy as a substructural piece allowing one the freedom to express the life they’ve been born to live. This is exercised through his creation of the Cryptowoke Financial Sustainability Movement.

I'm a former Brand Marketing Strategist for the National Basketball Association, I demystify Financial Literacy and share how I went from loyal, corporate employee to financially sustainable living off my savings and investments.

I teache personal finance, business and career development skills that encompasses much more than financial education. I add an instilling knowledge and confidence in my clients/students so they can experience—sometimes for the first time in their lives—financial dignity by simply enabling the ability to live off your savings and investments. This practice then leads to the creation of intergenerational wealth and sustainability.

I also own a renewable energy company based in the U.S. and Costa Rica focusing on creating STEAM and solar solutions for sustainable living.

I am a holistic-centered community health worker with a focus as a perinatal support specialist, childbirth educator, lactation & breastfeeding specialist, and homebirth midwifery student. I am a mother to 5 wonderful humans and married to an incredibly supportive spouse of a decade. I am on various statewide, local, and national committees centered around birth, breastfeeding, and maternal and infant morbidity and mortality. 

I am the Chief Executive Officer of a for profit business, M*Body Options Perinatal Support Services which offers education and support during the entire perinatal and postpartum period for pregnant persons and their families. I also am the Founder and Executive Director of Southern Appalachia Perinatal and Wellness Collective whose sole focus is to train additional perinatal support specialist and provide no cost services to African American/Black birthing persons to help minimize the high incidence of maternal and infant morbidity and mortality in my community. 

My hobbies include:  gardening, sewing, crafting, herbalism/plant medicine, research, roller skating, hiking, camping, and outdoor adventures with my family.

fields.BIO:
My work thrives at the intersection of community, and innovation. 

Born and raised in Savannah, I am a graduate of the University of Georgia. In 2013, I became the founding executive director of the Georgia Farmers Market Association (GFMA). In this role,  I worked with large and small  communities across our state, throughout the country and around the world. The Just Food program I initiated  in partnership with  UGA's  Department of Agribusiness and the USDA- AMS offers a community led sliding scale farmers market/ CSA hybrid to places with limited access to fresh, local produce. 
As someone who consistently brings diverse communities together to solve shared problems, I understand that authentic engagement requires commitment, consistency and reverence. I  know the immense long-term benefits obtained when one leads with intention and patience. 
I have served as a board member for the national Farmers Market Coalition, a 2018 Well-Being Impact Area Advisor for the Community Foundation of Atlanta, and an advisor for Tuskegee University’s Organic Farming Project.  I was  also chosen to participate in CARE USA’s first Growing Solidarity fellowship. This offered me the opportunity to travel to Côte d'Ivoire  to share and learn with both International representatives from CARE’s global health initiatives and indigenous leadership in a local village.  

In 2021, I helped design Georgia's first leadership fund specifically designed to honor black womxn leaders in our state. I also served on Mailchimp's Forward Project: An innovative approach to funding creative solutions. 
In my current role as Senior Director of Community Innovation at the Center for Civic Innovation,  I have cultivated a network of community leaders:  subject matter experts,  activists,  academics,  and other key Stakeholders around the issue of inequity in Atlanta's philanthropic ecosystem. In August 2020, I  led a discovery process with over 50 local nonprofit leaders,  reviewed data collected by CCI's policy team  and organized a group of impactful black women who have created a series of recommended changes and implementation strategies for Atlanta philanthropy. Currently, I am working with a group of black growers  and farmers market leaders  (in partnership with Farmers Market Coalition) to curate an anti-racist toolkit that will be made available to farmers market leaders across the country. 
My commitment to equitable local communities started at birth.  I am the daughter of the late Civil rights  Attorney Sage Brown; a decorated Vietnam veteran who was hand-picked by civil rights leaders to desegregate Chatham County Public Schools.  My mother was committed to educating youth; serving as both a principal of a local elementary school and a lead Sunday school teacher at the small church we attended  in rural south Georgia.   As a mother of 3,  the foundation of expanding impact by quilting family into the community continues through me.
 
An avid cook, a hobbyist floral arranger, and a tinker of tinctures,  I love to share my home with friends and neighbors who frolic through my garden and sample the Gullah Geechee dishes of my childhood.  You’d be surprised how effectively folk can work together when a delicious, homemade meal is shared. Healing happens.

So, that we all may thrive together as a collective people with a new African consciousness .

fields.BIO:
Scheril Murray Powell, Esq.- Bio
Scheril Murray Powell, Esq. is an Agricultural, Cannabis, and Dietary Supplement Attorney at Doumar, Allsworth, Laystrom, Voigt, Adair, and Dishowitz LLP.   She is the Chair of the Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion Sub-Committee of the ASTM D37 Committee.   Scheril also serves as the Director of Business Development of Creative Services, a FCRA Compliance, Background Screening, and Security Firm.  The Daily Business Review has named her one of the Top 12 Cannabis Attorney’s in Florida.  Her practice covers both the Marijuana and Hemp Industries, specializing in Cannabinoid legalization and UK Novel Foods registration.  She is a Florida licensed Hemp Farmer and is a Research Farmer for the University of Florida.  Scheril serves on the Board of one of the oldest Cannabis Advocacy Organizations, Patients Out of Time.  

She is the former Executive Director of the Black Farmers and Agriculturalists of Florida and former Director of Federal Affairs for the Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services.  Scheril is on the Hemp Pilot Program Advisory Board for the University of Florida and serves on the Broward County, Florida Medical Marijuana Advisory Board, The Tamarac North Lauderdale Chamber of Commerce Foundation, and a Board Member of The Unprescribed.org (a non-profit focused on Veteran Suicides).  She was a Founding Board Member for the U.S. Hemp Builders Association (not to be confused with the U.S. Hemp Building Association Foundation).  She is also President of consulting firm Green Sustainable Strong, LLC. 

 In her spare time she volunteers with the Winrock Foundation delivering Marketing training to Farmers in Ghana, Africa.  In 2018, she was a recipient of the Crohns Foundation Blood, Sweat, and Tears Award, and the Cannabis Business Award's Industry MVP Award.  She is former In House Counsel for Sunflora/ Your CBD Store and former In House Counsel for Green Roads World.  She is a graduate of Florida International University College of Law.  As a Cannapreneur, Scheril is the President of Canna Headhunters, a staffing agency in the Cannabis Industry that connects Cannabis talent to opportunities.  She has been selected to present at a number of Cannabis Conferences including the South East Cannabis Conference The Hemp and CBD Expo in the United Kingdom, The American Bar Association Cannabis Symposium: “From Regs to Riches”, the Cannabis Science Conference, Tuskegee University Professional Agricultural Workers Conference, the Women Grow Leadership Summit,  the Emerge Conference, the U.S. Cannabis Conference, Canex Jamaica Conference, South East Cannabis Conference, SHE-CANN,  Cannaday, The University of the West Indies Caribbean Neuroscience Conference,  Women Grow Leadership Summit, National Association of State Credit Unions,  The Kentucky Hemp Convention, The Kentucky State Hemp Symposium, the University of Technology Jamaican Medical Cannabis Integrated Symposium, The Women of Cannabis Conference, the Cannabis Science Conference, Detroit’s Canna Con, Florida Medical Marijuana Conference, and Canna-Ed Conference hosted by the Florida Cannabis Coalition. She has been asked to speak at Jamaica’s Pharmacological Board Mandatory Meetings and Jamaica Bureau of Standards meetings based on her international reputation as a Cannabis Expert.  In May of 2019, she planned and hosted the 1st Annual Cannurban-Unifest Agricultural Symposium in collaboration with the City of Lauderdale Lakes and the FAMU-Cannurbian Hemp Town Hall with Florida A&M University.  Scheril was the regular Cannabis Law expert on Cannabis Law Radio every Saturday morning on Cannabis Life Radio and launched a Cannabis Talk Show called “Terps in the City” in Summer of 2019. She presented at the National Association of Black Journalists and National Association of Hispanic Journalists Joint Conference in August 2016 on the topic of: “Exposing the Truth: Getting Access to Audio and Video Evidence in Police Involved Shootings”. Scheril served as both the Secretary and Treasurer of the FIU College of Law Alumni Board. While at FIU Law, she was the Charter President of the Palm Beach ABA Student Organization and a member and coach of the Board of Advocates Negotiation Team. In 2013, Scheril won the FIU Law Intramurals Negotiation Competition, also she and her partner won the ABA Southern Region Negotiation Competition. In 2014, she and her partner came in 2nd place in the Nelson Mandela International Negotiation Competition and she was awarded the distinction of Best Overall Negotiator for her efforts. Scheril served on the Black Law Student Association’s National Board for two years and is passionate about eradicating sex trafficking and other social justice issues such as police brutality. She has interned at the State Attorney’s office in the 15th Judicial Circuit of Palm Beach County and for two judges of the 17th Judicial Circuit of Broward County. In the summer of 2014, she served as an Anti-Defamation League Summer Associate. She believes that practicing the law and advocacy for the disadvantaged go hand in hand. She is an activist and has dedicated her time and resources to promoting awareness, access to educational resources, and support for survivors of domestic violence and trafficking. She has a Facebook page called “Police Chronicles” which documents national police interactions with the community. She mentors Pre-Law and Law School students of diverse backgrounds and has been a speaker at the Black and Hispanic Prelaw Conference, the Diversity Prelaw Conference, and the HBCU Prelaw Summit and Expo. Law is a second career for Scheril. She spent over a decade in the wireless industry working for T-Mobile, USA; T-Mobile, UK; RIM BlackBerry; and MetroPCS as a Customer Retention Strategist and Marketing Interface Manager rolling out training, technical change, cultural change, and process improvement projects Nationwide. Scheril received her undergraduate Business Management degree from Florida Atlantic University with a minor in Marketing where she pledged Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc. and served as the Student Government Senate Speaker for seven campuses.

fields.BIO:
Known as Billy to his friends, William J. Rennalls is the embodiment of what a Cannabis Expert and Consultant should be.   Mr. Rennalls has experience in the Cannabis Markets of the Caribbean, the United States, and Canada.   Born and raised on the island of Jamaica, Billy had intimate knowledge of agriculture and horticulture from an early age.   He had an aptitude for science, specifically the mechanics of how things work and how to optimize plant growth.  At the young age of 16, he graduated from Campion College  and went on to explore the world, starting with attending the University of Western Ontario.  His college experience led him to a period of self reflection and exploration of his beliefs.  Billy felt drawn to the tenets of the Rastafarian faith.   Billy returned to Jamaica with a Canadian education, his head adorned with dreadlocks, and ready to begin an intellectual and spiritual journey.  He encountered much prejudice and discrimination because of his choice to become a Rasta.  Despite the difficulty finding a job or an opportunity to use his skills and education, Billy found solace in the Rastafarian Community that embraced him. He embarked on a learning excursion at a self determined pace, flanked by many Rastafarian teachers and returned to one of his first loves, which was agriculture. 

As he learned more about plants and delved into apiculture, he saw comparisons between plants ,bees and humans.   He explored the origins of many natural remedies and found the Cannabis Plant had a significant amount of healing benefits.  This discovery ignited a thirst for knowledge which caused him to read everything that he could and ultimately he grew ganja while conducting his own research experiments.  He became a legalization activist and influencer, but had to identify a way to generate revenue to fund his living expenses and his research.   Billy was one of the Partners in One of the First Front Loader Waste Removal Companies  on the island which became a hugely successful company.  He would tell people that he was the Mighty Garbage man and  lived and slept garbage.   After a number of years, he diversified his pursuits by entering into the Waste Water Management  in Scrap metal and the  oil business while designing various waste to energy proposals for various governments.  His love of agriculture, nature and his knowledge of waste management/ energy creation came together in his vision to create a zero  waste environment through raising awareness around the various uses for waste and  Biomass.   Mr. Rennalls is Currently CEO for Emerald Waste Industries Masterlube and Lubehaus Distributors, He is the LATAM Director for International Commodities Management Consultants Corp,  and Director of Aquatic Solutions and Innovations.

fields.BIO: Adah Parris is co-Founder of Ism.Earth, an innovation lab and creative studio. Adah is also Chair of Mental Health First Aid England (MHFA UK). She is an enthusiastic curator of people, patterns and stories. Her work sits at the intersection of humans, technology, ecology, innovation and art. Adah focuses on democratising the innovation process by changing how we experience the world.

Adam C. Powers is an African American storyteller, green energy expert, teacher, technologist, artist, botanist, A.R. & V.R. developer, and (most importantly) a father of a brilliant little seven-year-old boy. 
Adam co-founded a nonprofit called Key Tech Labs, where the mission is to bring emerging technologies to underprivileged areas to help create self-sustainable communities. This means they bring new-age tech to communities in need to teach youth how to utilize the tech to empower themselves and their community. The best example is their Farmbot class, where they bought a Farmbot (which is an open-source C.N.C. machine, that when put over a garden bed, will weed, water, and seed the garden all by itself) and brought the robot to his old middle school, and taught youth how to build it and place it on a garden bed in the neighborhood. 

In 2018, Adam started his solar career working for a Seattle solar startup, Omnidian. There he worked at Omnidian as a Technical Support Specialist and learned much about the industry as a whole. After George Floyd's death, he felt a need to do more for his community and with the help of internal Omnidian stakeholders, he started the Civic Action Committee in Omnidian, which is a J.E.D.I program (Justice Equity Diversity and Inclusion). The main focus is to address energy poverty issues through energizing black-owned Farmland as well as creating a diverse pipeline of Workforce Development into the solar industry. Adam is currently part of Amicus O&M's J.E.D.I initiative and a member of B.O.S.S. (Black Owners of solar services). He is currently leading the development of a national solar program through B.O.S.S.' education committee. In addition, he is on the board of a nonprofit Shark garden that has built a 1.9 acre urban garden in the heart of Burien, WA, that produces over 2,000 tons of organic food per year. He is currently in the process of working with local solar companies Sphere Solar & A.R. solar to install mini solar microgrids on urban farmland. When the systems are installed, these farms will not only just be generating food, but they will also generate energy and water (through an air to water generator) on the land as well. 

His goal is to showcase this green tech to the community and show the world a path to a socially and environmentally just future. One where people, technology, and the environment coexist harmoniously creating an ecosystem designed for all to thrive and live their best lives. Grounded in practical steps and processes that each of us can do today with the resources we have at our disposal.

fields.BIO:
Thomas ‘T.J.’ Loftin is today’s most prolific expert on gentrification and economics. Threatened by mass gentrification and corporate expansion across the United States, small business owners and long-time residents are increasingly at risk for displacement.  Loftin continues the urgent fight for strategies and solutions by releasing the new edition of his top-selling 2018 release, Monetizing Gentrification: Building Black Ownership.  

A native of Compton, CA,‘T.J.’ Loftin has always been at the forefront of community representation and vitality.  He has a long history of spotting and fighting wrongful politics especially when disproportionally affecting Black communities.  During the last 15 years, his voice and collaborative efforts range from advocating for residents effected by the Section 8 scandal of Antelope Valley, California, to the mass displacement of the primarily Black communities within urban Los Angeles.  Silicon Valley, Metro, Elon Musk and SpaceX, NFL, and an array of other major corporations swooped into the region staking claim on property and businesses.  A seasoned investor, Loftin predicted this domino effect and its endangering homeownership, nationally.
Loftin is a well-renowned international business leader_ celebrity car builder and manufacturer, real estate, land development, gentrification expert, media, public speaker, author, and wealth coach.  He has been hands-on in building businesses, industries, and communities.  Crossing paths with the late ancestor Dr. Sebi (world-renowned herbalist and celebrity holistic healer.  Actor, entertainer, and television host, Nick Cannon is completing the highly-anticipated Dr. Sebi documentary, as started by the late Nipsey Hussle), at Leimert Park would forever impact his life.  His successful fight for vendor rights against the City of Los Angeles would evolve into a larger fight, globally.
T.J. has taught the youth, and has been an advisor to Compton and Inglewood school districts.  To date, he has toured 24 states, analyzing various states of gentrification within Black Communities, enabling him to write the ultimate handbook, Monetizing Gentrification: Building Black Ownership. This new edition provides even more strategies and solutions, illustrated in vibrant color!  Buy your copy today at  www.tjloftin.com.
NOTES TO EDITORS
Thomas T.J. Loftin resides in Atlanta, GA. For media inquiries, please contact the author at info@tjloftin.com. For booking speaking engagements call (310) 619-3954 with pricing, availability, and topic.  Coaching and training services at www.tjloftin.com

fields.BIO:
K. Rashid Nuri, CEO
K. Rashid Nuri had a powerful "burning bush" revelation while a student at Harvard. The experience set him on a global food odyssey, managing agricultural operations throughout the U.S. and in 35 countries in Europe, Asia, and Africa.  One of Rashid's earliest work experiences in agriculture was as the Director of Farm Operations for Salaam Agricultural Systems in Bronwood, Georgia, owned by the Nation of Islam. He managed 13,000 acres of land in Georgia and Alabama, valued at $20 million. Rashid also directed production of commodity and vegetable crops, poultry, dairy, beef, horses, sheep and bees. His work also included developing agricultural properties, defining markets and distribution patterns, maintaining budgetary control, reviewing and evaluating farm operations, selecting personnel, brokering land sales and negotiating contracts. 

Rashid's global agricultural service began with his position as Regional Investment Manager for Cargill in Singapore, preparing general business plans for the region producing more than $500 million in revenues. He introduced computerized feed formulation to Southeast Asia regions that improved efficiency, lowered overhead and increased revenues. Rashid also served in Bangladesh, Hong Kong, India, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Pakistan, the Philippines, Taiwan, Thailand, Singapore, Sri Lanka, and South Korea. He then became Managing Director for Cargill Nigeria Limited and Cargill Ventures Limited in Lagos, Nigeria, where he researched and managed the company's entry to the Nigerian marketplace for corn, wheat, sorghum, cottonseed, cotton lint, palm kernel cake, cocoa, rubber and sugar. He also supervised trading and warehousing from start-up through the generation of more than $50 million in revenues.  

During the Clinton Administration, Rashid served at USDA as Deputy Vice-President for the Commodity Credit Corporation and Deputy Administrator for the Farm Service Agency and Foreign Agriculture Service. He formulated policy for administrative operations affecting some 34,000 employees in more than 3,000 sites. In addition, he was directly responsible for a workforce of 2,200 employees. His duties included maintaining accounting, financial and claims system activities for yearly outlays ranging from $18-24 billion, including budget analyses, forecasts, and tracking of administrative expenses, appropriated funds, corporate funds and funds allocated from other sources.  

During his years at USDA, Rashid saw—up close—the abuses and inefficiencies of Big Ag. Under the leadership of Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, Rashid commissioned the Miller Report, which chronicled the role of Big Ag and the U.S. Government in the century-long destruction of Black Farmers. Unfortunately, the report was buried, and Rashid was fired.  Four years later, the truths contained in the Miller Report reached the courtroom in the landmark Pigford class action lawsuit against the USDA, in which Black farmers detailed how the agency consistently worked against the progress and success of Black farmers. The case was ultimately settled for more than $1 billion, a fraction of the damage endured by Black farmers and their families.

After his experience at the USDA, Rashid's vision of community food sovereignty and food equity emerged with total clarity. He brought that vision to Atlanta in 2006, founding Truly Living Well Center for Natural Urban Agriculture (TLW). TLW became Atlanta's premier urban agricultural organization, growing tons of chemical-free, nutritious food, providing jobs and educating communities about food, nutrition and self-sufficiency.  
As CEO of The Nuri Group, Rashid is working to expand equitable access to the tools for success in agriculture through education, funding, partnerships and appropriate regulations. Rashid is the author of Growing Out Loud: Journey of a Food Revolutionary, which chronicles his journeys and the failing state of the food supply. Growing Out Loud offers timely and valuable guidance for the new food movement. 
----

fields.BIO:
I am an organizer, energy shifter, and black girl magician working toward collective liberation through community organizing, soulful facilitation, and healing justice.

R’Yana Michele is a Black queer ritualmaker, creative intuitive messenger, and healing artist. She creates containers that edify authenticity, home, and belonging. They came into this world on a mission to create expressions of the divine mother through:  facilitating safety & sanctuary, uplifting the healing arts, and practicing land stewardship. 

R’Yana dreams of a world full of magic and liberation for black people and seeks to create interventions for the complete wholeness of Black community. R’Yana currently offers her gifts as Principal/Healing Artist of Conjure Community Healing Arts (www.conjurecha.org), a steering committee member with New Economy of Tennessee Cooperative Loan Fund (www.co-opsnow.org/net-fund) and member-owner of Water Bear Cooperative Land Project (www.waterbearcooplandproject.com). As a Black Southern Hoodoo healer, organizer, abolitionist, and earth steward, R’Yana is dedicated to cultivating radically loving and inclusive cultures that heal.

The areas of my work have centered on housing and land justice, decriminalization of blackness, prison/police abolition and anti-oppression education. In this iteration of my growth and development, my focuses are community safety and wellness, Black survival and maroon spaces, and alternative finance/economics. I am currently the program associate for a philanthropic loan fund for Black organizing, loan officer and steering committee member for New Economy Tennessee (NET) Cooperative Loan Fund, and growing my own community practice - Conjure Community Healing Arts. 

My roots start with the coastal South of Houston, TX and the Piney Woods of Marshall, TX. Growing up black, womyn, southern, and working class have shaped my values and influence everything that I do. I have learned first hand in the face of disaster the ways that our survival is threatened and comprised. Through the lack of community infrastructure, access to resources, and unorganized people power, we are operating in the midst of great danger. For the interest of ourselves and future generations, we must be building the world we want now. And I am on the path toward that. I have a passionate desire to develop community and cultural interventions that transform the material conditions of Black people. I strive to create for black, brown, queer, working class, and poor people – My people. I deeply believe in the power of institutions and communal sustainability which is maintained through organizing. I want to be a movement healer and host. I have been charged by my ancestors to create home, create safety, create place for our people. In the 3-4 years, I am working to create a Black sustainable training and ecological center in Tennessee and in Texas. Safe houses, places of sanctuary and renewal. Our people are tired and ready. In the face of violence, harm, and indignities toward Black people in the global diaspora and South, we need movements that awaken, refresh, love, and hold our people. We need the skills to fill this deficit. There is a need and responsibility to do the profound work of reclamation of self and culture. As we imagine a new way, we must transform along with it. Conjure channels the Black ancestral traditions of "making a way out of no way" to save our selves. Self-determination. Culture. Community. Healing. Restoration. Conjure strives to model a village culture and practice a regenerative care economy. I love creating liberatory containers, such as workshops, training, and convenings. 

As a Black Southern organizer, abolitionist, and earth steward, I am dedicated to embodying an accepting and affirming home for all and cultivating radically loving, inclusive cultures that heal. I wish to build together a movement that is not only critical and progressive but is healing and holistic.

I served 6-years as a Secretarial appointee to the federal Biomass R&D Technical Advisory Committee, which advises government on biomass R&D, and  I have a BS in Science, from Union College, and have studied Law and Business at NYU.

We will be extracting almost 4 times the atmospheric CO 2, as an equal acreage of trees, when Biomass Sorghum, our preferred Bio-Crop, is planted outdoors, to remediate brownfield sites and to provide other environmental services, and roughly 9 times as much, when Biomass Sorghum is planted in our proposed Vertical Bio-Crop Farms (VBF's), to capture CO 2 from the flue gasses of large emitters.

In 2010, Dragon was appointed by the Atlanta City Council to the Atlanta Commission on Women to lead change related to women’s entrepreneurship. Yvonne participates as an entrepreneurial expert and business coach for local and national events including Atlanta City Council Ceasar Mitchell’s Back to Business event and Black Enterprise’s Annual Small Business Summit.

In the span of her career, Yvonne has coached or trained over 300 businesses, including 50 startups and advised over 50 CEOs of small businesses.

fields.BIO: Sustainable Georgia Futures (“SF”) is a nonpartisan grassroots organization dedicated to creating green economy pathways for Black and people of color. We are a Black-woman-led collective of expert organizers and community leaders working to build power in marginalized communities to advance an inclusive economy and environmental justice. Sustainable Georgia Futures seeks to address two of our nation’s crises: climate change and systemic racism. We address these crises by creating viable pathways for communities of color, especially Black communities, to access jobs and entrepreneurship  in the growing green economy through relational organizing.

fields.BIO:
I am Jawno, a creative organizer and gardener dedicated to cultivating just, regenerative futures through accessible cultural experiences, inspiring creative works, and good trouble. In my philanthropic work, I strive to connect Black, Indigenous, and other Global Majority communities with the tools and resources necessary to realize resource sovereignty and climate resilience.

As a descendant of Indigenous African stewards in Nigeria and Southern Black farmers in the Southeast U.S., I have witnessed firsthand the impacts of environmental degradation and industrial agriculture, which have displaced my family from the land they have harmonized with for generations. My pre-med studies at Stanford University deepened my understanding of how environmental harm exacerbates climate catastrophes and adversely affects the health and livelihoods of marginalized communities.

After graduating from Stanford in 2021, I focused on climate change and environmental justice, particularly in the realms of permaculture, agroecology, and traditional Indigenous agricultural practices. My work aims to explore and promote these interconnected practices as powerful alternatives to the dominant modes of land and resource extraction that jeopardize our planet today.

Currently, as a Program Associate at the Waverley Street Foundation, I collaborate with our team and external partners to design and deliver grants focused on natural farming, renewable energy, and joy. I have also contributed significantly to shaping foundation strategies, especially around global youth activism and land-based liberation.

I started Get Free Food to inspire and empower communities to reclaim their food sovereignty through joyous, culturally resonant gatherings. By collaborating with local farmers, chefs, artists, community orgs, and educators, we ensure that everyone has access to healthy, free food while fostering a sense of belonging and regeneration. We envision a food movement where everyone can find belonging — place by place, moment by moment, meal by meal. We must make the good food revolution irresistible.

My passion for Black and Indigenous liberation, climate justice, and youth education is complemented by my interests in poetry, food and land sovereignty, revolutionary aesthetics, and Afrofuturism. I continue to engage in intergenerational, intersectional, and international efforts to build just resource systems, reinvigorate sovereignty, and create sanctuaries for marginalized communities.

fields.BIO:
I was born in Oakland, California in 1947 and raised in a two parent home with my three siblings in San Francisco. I have five adult
children whom I raised as a single parent in East Palo Alto, California. I am the grandmother of four granddaughters and four
grandsons. I joined the Black Power movement while attending UC Berkeley (67-69) as an undergrad student in social work. It was
there I became a Citizen of the Republic of New Africa (RNA) and experienced cointelpro infiltration in the Bay Area during the
aftermath of the RNA 11 in Jackson, Mississippi IN 1971.
In a sociology class at UC Berkeley (1967), I was among 20 students who traveled to Washington D. C. to study the Poor Peoples
Campaign where I witnessed civil rights activists attempting to force the government to meet the demands Martin Luther King had
proposed before his assassination. While attending UCB, I was employed as the administrative assistant of the Ethnic Studies
department at the University of San Francisco. In my last semester UCB, I joined demonstrations with students, community residents
and members of RNA to fight against Western Civilization Curriculum at UC Berkeley for an Ethnic Studies department. I managed to
graduate but was denied graduate school due to my involvement in my fight for “Third World Studies.”
After walking out of my graduation (received BA degree in Social Work) in support of the students who were incarcerated due to the
demonstrations, I later traveled to Ghana as the youngest of 175 Afrikan American educators in 1969. Educators included noted
scholars Drs. C. Eric Lincoln and Betty Shabazz. I received a certification in Afrikan Culture and History at the University of Accra. I
returned to the states and moved to D.C. from the Bay Area where I was inspired to become an educator. I returned to California
and received my masters in elementary education at San Francisco State University (1972).
I moved to East Palo Alto and taught in their public schools for 10 years. In the summer of 1982, I traveled to Ghana and Nigeria
with my five children (ages 2-7 at the time). I wanted them to have a different vision of Africa then what most people were
experiencing on television. Shortly after returning, I retired from the public schools in 1983 and became the founder and co-founder
of several independent Afrikan Centered schools, most notably Shule Mandela Academy. I became a member of the Council of
Independent Institutions (CIBI ) and was the CIBI Northern California Convener for several years. After attending the State of the Black
Race in Los Angeles in 1983, I returned to co-found a Rites of Passage Group for Girls called the Sisters of Tomorrow (SOT). I
presently work with the SOT Atlanta chapter as an elder. To raise funds for Shule Mandela Academy, I started the
Collard Greens Cultural Festival in 1998 which continues to this day in EPA and the Metro-Atlanta Region. In 2001, I attended the World Conference on Racism in
Durban, South Africa where it was declared "Slavery was a crime against Humanity". 
I became a resident the City of Decatur, Georgia in 2006 with my disabled son. Three of my daughters received their BA from
Howard University and one continued to receive her masters at the University of Pennsylvania. In 2007, I completed a doctoral
program at Nova Southeastern University in Fort Lauderdale, Florida. My dissertation was entitled, “A case study of African Centered
Schools”. In Georgia, my community activism continued. In 2010, I started the CGCF festival
(www.collardgreensculturalfestival.com) in the Metro-Atlanta area; I am presently the co-chair of the Metro-Atlanta Council of
Elders Support Team; I am a member of Afrikan Community Centers and Us Lifting Us; I co-founded the Sustainable Afrikan
Communities (www.blacksustainabilitysummit.com); I am an Elder member of the Atlanta chapter of Sisters of Tomorrow; a
member of the Atlanta N’COBRA chapter; an Elder on the Advisory Board of
Nsoromma School; a member of African Women Economic Commission (AWEC); on the board of directors to build an International Center for dialogue between Afrikan American women and continental Afrikan women; and presently I am sit on the Board of Trustees at Kilombo Academic and
Cultural Institute located in Decatur, Georgia. Presently I am the Chair of the Metro-Atlanta Pan African Federalist Movement as well
as the secretary general of the Regional PAFM North America. I am also a member of the Beacon Hill Black Alliance for Humanity where I co-chair the local reparations committee for reparations in the City of Decatur. My most recent involvement was helping to organize the Knowledge Keepers - Circle of Elders first annual event in 2023. Finally, I practice Yoruaba/Ifa traditonal religion.                               
My recent travels were to Nigeria in 2018  (where I was crowned a chief), Ghana in 2019 (with all my children and grandchildren), and Tanzania in 2022.

fields.BIO:
Gathering Roots Vision
Wellness in community encompasses artistic expression, all spiritualities, sustainable land stewardship for food sovereignty, and space to witness and heal.  We value cultural connection to each other and the land. All those in the Black community deserve a space where they can BE all of their intersectional selves while in respite.

Further, by providing cultural explorations of the land, traditional healing gatherings, and social justice coalition building, our collective lives the intention to lift the oppression of generational trauma through liberation and joy!
